The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Corporate Briefs
                                                                                                               Corporate Briefs
                              
	 Godrej Consumer Products has fixed its rights issue price at Rs 123 per share to raise funds worth Rs 400 crore. The board of directors has approved a rights issue in a 1:7 ratio, wherein one equity share of a face value of Re 1 will be issued for every seven shares held. March 19 has been fixed as the record date for the issue. The company plans to utilise the proceeds of the issue to fund capital expenditure, payment of certain debts and investments in its subsidiary, Godrej Netherlands BV, and its joint venture, Godrej SCA Hygiene Ltd.                            
	 Maithan Ispat Ltd has raised Rs 73.3 crore from a consortium of ORIX Corporation and a unit of Infrastructure Leasing amp; Financial Services Ltd. The company will use these funds to complete an integrated steel plant in Kalinganagar, Orissa. The facility includes a universal heavy section mill with an annual capacity of 0.4 million tonnes per annum.                             
	 Kingfisher Airlines has been granted five-star airline status by Skytrax. Kingfisher has recently announced daily non-stop flights between Chennai and Trivandrum. Kingfisher Airlines now has 238 departures a day, serving 41 destinations with a fleet of 39 aircraft. The total number of weekly flights operated by the airlines is 1656.                             
	 TRF Ltd has launched a mobile stone crusher and screening plant in Jamshedpur. The plant will produce 20 mm stones from a feed size of 300 mm in a single-stage process. The crushing plant consists of a feeder, primary and secondary jaw crushers, conveyor belt, vibrating screens, supporting structures and drive arrangements.                            
	 Henkel India Ltd has received the Amity Corporate Excellence Award at the 10th International Business Summit and Research Conference 2008, held at Noida.                             
	 Airtel has launched m-commerce solutions such as mobile money transfer, post-paid bill payment and prepaid recharge. It will partner ICICI Bank, HDFC Bank, the SBI, Corporation Bank and Visa. The solution has been developed by mChek.                                                                                                                    ADVERTISEMENT                   
